		</td>
        
	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  valign="top" class="msg" width="100%" >
         
          <b>Processors</b> <br>  <br> There are two kinds of processors available for gamers:  Intel Pentiums, and AMD Athlons. <br>  <br> <b>Intel Pentiums</b> <br>  <br> Types: <br> Pentium 4 (usually Hyperthreaded now) <br> Pentium 4 Extreme (much larger cache, much more expensive) (feedback needed) <br> Centrino (mobile processor, avoid in a desktop computer) <br> Celeron (smaller cache, less expensive, may be suitable for EQ2) (feedback needed) <br>  <br> Notes: <br> Hyperthreading doesn't make the game run faster, it only helps if you're trying to multi-task while gaming.  But it's pretty much standard in the higher-end P4s now.   <br> The watchword on speed is to get the fastest processor you can afford. <br> With Intel, you want to shoot for an 800mhz motherboard and processor interface.  Older 533mhz systems are still around and should be avoided, although the difference in overall performance is not great. <br>  <br> <b>Can I upgade my system?</b> <br> The answer to this depends on the system you currently have.  If you have a system with a DDR RAM and a 533mhz or 800mhz bus speed, it's quite possible that the answer to your question is &quot;yes&quot; -- a faster processor may be available.  If not, you're probably out of luck.   <br>  <br> (I could use some input here in terms of helping people pick out the right processor in upgrading their system.  Post below and I'll integrate your information here.) <br>  <br>  <br> -------------- <br>  <br> <b>AMD Athlons</b> <br>  <br> There are two kinds of Athlon processors: 32-bit and 64-bit.  The 32-bit Athlons are marked &quot;XP&quot;, and the 64-bit Athlons are marked either &quot;Athlon 64&quot; or &quot;Athlon 64 FX&quot; (a premium brand; much more expensive).  Opterons should be avoided -- they're designed for modeling workstations and such.   <br>  <br> Durons should be avoided; AMD cancelled that line.  A new Sempron line is out I think, but I don't know much about it.  (Feedback needed.)  These are budget chips, like the Celeron, and may work for EQ2. <br>  <br> <b>Can I upgrade my system?</b> <br>  <br> If you have an Athlon XP system with DDR RAM, the answer is likely &quot;yes&quot;, some upgrade options remain open for you to get a faster XP processor.  If you have an older Athlon system, you'll probably need a new motherboard.   <br>  <br> If you have a 64-bit system, I wouldn't worry about upgrading at all.  If you're lagging in a game, you probably need to focus on getting a faster video card. <br>  <br> If you have an Athlon XP system rated at &quot;2800+&quot; or higher and need more speed, you also probably should focus more on the video card instead of the main system. <br>  <br>  <br> <b>CPU Pins</b> <br>  <br> One of the key areas for confusion today in the Athlon wold (and soon in the Intel world, if not already) is the number of pins used to connect the processor to the motherboard.  There are already several configurations to watch out for.   <br>  <br> In Athlon XP systems, this is simple -- it's just not an issue.  Don't worry about it.  (Can someone confirm that for me please? Thanks.) <br>  <br> In Athlon 64 systems, this is a real problem.  But like I said above, if you have a 64-bit system and want to upgrade you really should focus on the video card at this point.  But if you REALLY want to upgrade the processor, and you really don't want to buy a new motherboard, you need to figure out how many pins are connecting the processor and make sure you get a new processor with the same number.  If it doesn't say anywhere, it's probably the older 754 (?) pin type.  Newer 939-pin types are typically marked in a prominent way. 
          
		  <span class="info">
