	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  width="155" valign="top" class="ultrasmall" nowrap>
        <a href="showProfile.aspx?memid=57" class="subhead" target="_blank">Jani</a><br>
        
		  <script>titleAndStar(1493,-73,false,false,"","")</script><br>
		  <div align="center"><img src="http://ghguild.com/forum/upfiles/57/3AD8373F14924036B3B739C8404B1D39.gif" border=0 align="absmiddle"></div><br>
          Posts:  1493<br>
          
          Joined:  11/1/2002 <br>
          
          Status: <span class='offline'>offline</span>
        
		  <img src="image/blank.gif" align="right" border="0" width="155" height="1">
		</td>
        
	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  valign="top" class="msg" width="100%" >
         
          Raid 0 is good if you move around lots of large files, which is something most of the people don't do often. I'm talking about video files, CD/DVD images etc. Those move with almost double speed with raid 0. <br>  <br> With typical desktop use you're using a lot of small files here and there, files that are fragmented all around the disk etc etc. In that kind of use seek time means everything. Want performance? Get a Raptor, or an SCSI-drive. <br>  <br> I'm not really convinced about the benefits of NCQ either on desktop use. It's being advertised based on a high I/O-count per second, but I'd like to see some real life tests first. <br> Server use is a whole different matter. <br>  <br> EDIT: Still, my next secondary drive will almost certainly be a 300-500 gigabyte Seagate with NCQ. 
          
